commitResults.messageBody:

classes which includes:

* Abstract class: Command
* Classes extending Command class: AddDeadlineCommand, AddEventCommand,

AddTodoCommand, DeleteCommand, ExitCommand, ListCommand,

MarkAsDoneCommand, MarkAsUndoneCommand

* Classes: Ui, Storage, Parser, TaskList, Duke

commitResults.messageTitle: Adding assertions to UI elements and task index
commitResults.messageBody:
The code has some assumptions about the UI elements
being present and task indexes being positive at runtime.

However this might not be the case, so missing UI elements and
negative task indexes can lead to unexpected behaviours.

Adding assertions can help us to catch these missing UI elements
and negative indexes and stop the execution.

Using assertions is preferable as it is easy to implement, easy to
disable for production while ensuring the code functions as expected.

Refer to this on the use of assertions:
https://nus-cs2103-ay2324s1.github.io/website/se-book-adapted/chapters/errorHandling.html#assertions

There are various points in the code where code quality can be
improved, including complicated header comments and deep nesting.

Complicated header comments can be confusing and less clear.
Deep nesting can make it difficult for the reader
to keep track of the logic.

Complicated header comments are replaced with
simpler ones for better readability.
Deep nesting code are replaced with simpler code while
making the happy path prominent so that the happy path
is less nested, providing better readability and maintainability.

Simpler header comments are preferred for better readability.
Less nesting and making happy path prominent provides
better code readability and maintainability.

Refer to this on dealing with code quality:
https://nus-cs2103-ay2324s1.github.io/website/schedule/week5/topics.html#W5-4
Adding assertions to UI elements and task index

commitResults.messageTitle: Add the ability to deal with duplicate items
commitResults.messageBody:
When the user has duplicated tasks in the duke.txt file, or inputs
duplicated tasks, it will be added into the list of tasks.

This makes it confusing for the users when reading the list
of task as those duplicated tasks are redundant.

When loading the file and inputting new tasks, the code now checks
for duplicated tasks and only add the unique task.
In checking for duplicated tasks, the code compares the task
description, and the dateTime where applicable
without considering the seconds.

Checking for duplicated tasks is preferred for better clarity
and readability for users when viewing the list of tasks.
Ignoring the seconds when checking for duplicated tasks is preferred
as the seconds is insignificant when viewing tasks but provides
more flexibility in checking for duplicated task.

Refer to this to deal with duplicated tasks:
https://nus-cs2103-ay2324s1.github.io/website/se-book-adapted/projectDuke/index.html#extensions-category-c
